---
import DocsLayout from "../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
import { Code } from "astro-expressive-code/components";---

<DocsLayout title="Schema Evolution">
  <h1>Schema Evolution</h1>
  <p>EntDB schemas evolve safely over time. The SDK enforces protobuf-like compatibility rules &mdash; you can always add, never remove.</p>

  <h2>Snapshot file format</h2>
  <p>
    <code>entdb init</code> writes a <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code>
    file that captures the committed shape of every node and edge type.
    This file is the baseline that <code>entdb check</code> compares
    every future schema change against in CI.
  </p>
  <Code code={`{
  "version": 2,
  "source": "schema.proto",
  "node_types": [
    {
      "type_id": 1,
      "name": "Task",
      "deprecated": false,
      "description": "",
      "data_policy": "PERSONAL",
      "fields": [
        { "field_id": 1, "name": "title",  "kind": "str",  "required": true,
          "pii": false, "enum_values": null, "default_value": "",
          "deprecated": false, "description": "" },
        { "field_id": 2, "name": "status", "kind": "enum", "required": false,
          "pii": false, "enum_values": ["todo", "done"], "default_value": "",
          "deprecated": false, "description": "" }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "edge_types": [
    {
      "edge_id": 1, "name": "HasComment",
      "from_type": "Task", "to_type": "Comment",
      "propagate_share": true, "data_policy": "BUSINESS",
      "deprecated": false, "description": ""
    }
  ]
}`} lang="json" />
  <p>
    The on-disk format is intentionally readable: reviewers can diff
    <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code> in a pull request just like source
    code. Type ids and field ids are pinned, so renames (which preserve
    ids) show up as a one-line change to <code>name</code> while real
    structural change diffs cleanly.
  </p>

  <h2>Workflow</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Bootstrap once</strong>: run <code>entdb init schema.proto</code>
      after the first schema is finalised. Commit
      <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code> to the repo. This is the baseline
      every future build is judged against.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Iterate freely</strong>: edit <code>schema.proto</code>,
      regenerate, run <code>entdb check schema.proto</code> locally
      &mdash; non-breaking changes print
      <code>[OK]</code> markers; breaking changes print
      <code>[BREAKING]</code> and exit non-zero.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Commit a snapshot bump only with the change</strong>: when
      you make a deliberate, compatible schema change, run
      <code>entdb init schema.proto --force</code> to refresh the
      baseline and include the updated <code>snapshot.json</code> in the
      same pull request. Reviewers see the schema diff and the
      snapshot diff together.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>CI gate</strong>: the CI job runs <code>entdb check
      schema.proto</code>. If anyone introduces a breaking change without
      refreshing the snapshot, CI fails before the change can land.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>What <code>entdb check</code> actually does, step by step:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Parse <code>schema.proto</code> via <code>parse_proto()</code>, producing in-memory <code>NodeInfo</code> / <code>EdgeInfo</code> records.</li>
    <li>Build a v2 snapshot dict from the parsed proto (same shape as <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code>).</li>
    <li>Load the baseline snapshot from <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code> (override with <code>--baseline</code>).</li>
    <li>Run <code>_check_compat(old, new)</code>, which iterates every node and edge type, every field, and every enum value, classifying each diff as breaking or non-breaking.</li>
    <li>Print one line per detected change. Exit <code>1</code> if any breaking change is present, <code>0</code> otherwise.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Compatible vs breaking changes</h2>
  <p>
    The lint rules implemented in
    <code>sdk/entdb_sdk/cli.py::_check_compat()</code> are the source of
    truth. The summary:
  </p>
  <table>
    <tr><th>Change</th><th>Status</th><th>Why</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Add a new node or edge type</td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>Old clients ignore unknown <code>type_id</code>s.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Add a new field</td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>Old payloads omit it; defaults apply on read.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Add new enum values (append)</td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>No existing row carries the new value.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rename a field</td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>On-disk payloads use <code>field_id</code>, not name &mdash; the rename touches generated code only.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rename a type</td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>Same reason &mdash; the wire identifier is <code>type_id</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Mark a field <code>deprecated</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>Lint warns at read sites; the field is still readable.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Change <code>acl_defaults</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span></td><td>Only affects <em>newly created</em> nodes.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Remove a field</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Existing payloads keyed by that <code>field_id</code> become unreadable through the new schema.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Remove a node or edge type</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Existing data references the removed <code>type_id</code> / <code>edge_id</code>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Change a field's <code>kind</code> (str ↔ int, etc.)</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>On-disk values can no longer be decoded as the new type.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Reuse a <code>type_id</code> or <code>field_id</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Collision with retired data.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Remove an enum value</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Existing rows may still hold the value.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Make an optional field required</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Pre-existing rows have no value for it.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Change <code>propagate_share</code> on an edge</td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Alters ACL inheritance for already-shared data.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Change an edge's <code>from_type</code> / <code>to_type</code></td><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span></td><td>Existing edges reference incompatible endpoints.</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>Versioning &amp; the WAL</h2>
  <p>
    Every WAL event carries a <code>schema_fingerprint</code> &mdash; the
    SHA-256 of the canonical schema at the time the producer wrote the
    event. Because payloads on disk are keyed by
    <code>field_id</code>, not field name, schema versioning is
    effectively free:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Renames change the fingerprint but leave on-disk bytes intact &mdash;
      the new schema can read all old events because the
      <code>field_id</code>s still match.
    </li>
    <li>
      Field additions change the fingerprint; old events simply lack the
      new <code>field_id</code> in their payload, and the field defaults
      apply on read.
    </li>
    <li>
      A breaking change (which CI should have rejected) would still
      <em>parse</em> at the WAL level (events are JSON keyed by id) but
      would mismatch when the applier tried to materialise the row,
      surfacing as a schema-fingerprint error rather than silent data
      corruption.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    There is no separate "schema version" integer: the fingerprint <em>is</em>
    the version, and any two snapshots with the same fingerprint are
    interchangeable.
  </p>

  <h2>Recovering from a bad snapshot</h2>
  <p>
    If a snapshot was committed with an incorrect baseline &mdash; e.g.
    someone ran <code>entdb init --force</code> against the wrong proto
    file and pushed the result &mdash; the symptom is a CI run that
    either passes a real breaking change or rejects something that's
    actually fine. Recovery:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Identify the last commit where the snapshot matched the deployed
      schema (usually the previous green CI build on
      <code>main</code>).
    </li>
    <li>
      Restore that <code>.entdb/snapshot.json</code> file:
      <Code code={`git checkout <good-sha> -- .entdb/snapshot.json`} lang="bash" />
    </li>
    <li>
      Re-run <code>entdb check schema.proto</code>. The diff against the
      restored baseline is the <em>real</em> set of changes since the
      last known-good schema.
    </li>
    <li>
      If those changes are intentional and compatible, run
      <code>entdb init schema.proto --force</code> to write a fresh
      snapshot, commit it, and push.
    </li>
    <li>
      If the live deployment has already accepted writes under the wrong
      fingerprint, no data is lost &mdash; field-id stability means the
      payloads remain readable. The fingerprint mismatch is itself the
      red flag and resolves once the snapshot is corrected.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>The Lifecycle</h2>

  <h3>Day 1: Initial Schema</h3>
  <Code code={`# schema.py — your first release
Task = NodeTypeDef(type_id=1, name="Task", fields=(
    field(1, "title", "str", required=True),
    field(2, "status", "enum", enum_values=("todo", "done")),
))

# Generate baseline snapshot
$ entdb init
# Commit .entdb/snapshot.json to git`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>Week 2: Add a Field</h3>
  <p><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span> Adding a new field with a new <code>field_id</code> is always safe:</p>
  <Code code={`Task = NodeTypeDef(type_id=1, name="Task", fields=(
    field(1, "title", "str", required=True),
    field(2, "status", "enum", enum_values=("todo", "done")),
    field(3, "priority", "int", default=0),  # NEW
))

$ entdb check
Schema compatible: 1 non-breaking change
  [OK] FIELD_ADDED: NodeType:Task.field:priority — added`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>Month 2: Add Enum Values</h3>
  <p><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span> Appending new enum values is safe:</p>
  <Code code={`field(2, "status", "enum", enum_values=("todo", "in_progress", "done", "archived"))`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h3>Month 3: Add a New Type</h3>
  <p><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span> New node types and edge types are always safe:</p>
  <Code code={`Subtask = NodeTypeDef(type_id=3, name="Subtask", fields=(
    field(1, "title", "str", required=True),
))

HasSubtask = EdgeTypeDef(edge_id=3, name="HasSubtask",
    from_type=Task, to_type=Subtask,
    propagate_share=True)`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h3>Month 6: Deprecate a Field</h3>
  <p><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span> Deprecation is allowed. The field stays in the schema but is flagged:</p>
  <Code code={`field(3, "priority", "int", default=0, deprecated=True)`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h3>Month 12: Add ACL Defaults</h3>
  <p><span class="badge badge-new">non-breaking</span> Changing <code>acl_defaults</code> only affects newly created nodes:</p>
  <Code code={`Task = NodeTypeDef(type_id=1, name="Task", fields=(...),
    acl_defaults=AclDefaults(tenant_visible=False))  # changed from True`} lang="sql" />

  <h2>Breaking Changes</h2>
  <p>These changes are <strong>rejected by <code>entdb check</code></strong> and will fail CI:</p>

  <table>
    <tr><th>Change</th><th>Why it breaks</th></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Remove a type</td><td>Existing data has this type_id</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Remove a field</td><td>Existing payloads may have this field</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Change a field's kind</td><td>Existing data has the old type</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Reuse a type_id or field_id</td><td>Collides with deprecated data</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Remove enum values</td><td>Existing data may have removed value</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Make optional field required</td><td>Existing nodes don't have it</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Change propagate_share</td><td>Affects ACL inheritance chain</td></tr>
    <tr><td><span class="badge badge-breaking">breaking</span> Change from_type / to_type</td><td>Existing edges reference old types</td></tr>
  </table>

  <h2>CI Integration</h2>

  <h3>Setup</h3>
  <Code code={`# pyproject.toml
[tool.entdb]
schema = "myapp.schema"
snapshot = ".entdb/snapshot.json"`} lang="plaintext" />

  <h3>CI Pipeline</h3>
  <Code code={`# .github/workflows/ci.yml
- name: Schema compatibility check
  run: entdb check`} lang="yaml" />

  <h3>Local Development</h3>
  <Code code={`# Check before commit
$ entdb check

# See what changed
$ entdb diff

# After intentional breaking change (rare, requires migration)
$ entdb snapshot --update`} lang="bash" />

  <h3>Automatic Test Validation</h3>
  <p>If <code>entdb-sdk</code> is installed, the pytest plugin automatically validates schema compatibility on every test run. No configuration needed.</p>

  <h2>Fingerprinting</h2>
  <p>The schema registry generates a SHA-256 fingerprint from the canonical schema. The server compares this fingerprint on every write:</p>
  <Code code={`# If fingerprint doesn't match, the server rejects the write
ExecuteAtomicResponse(
    success=False,
    error="Schema fingerprint mismatch: client=sha256:abc..., server=sha256:def..."
)`} lang="plaintext" />
  <p>This prevents deploying code with an incompatible schema.</p>

  <h2>Migration Strategies</h2>
  <p>For the rare case where you need a breaking change:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Parallel types</strong>: Create a new type (TaskV2) alongside the old one, migrate data</li>
    <li><strong>Soft migration</strong>: Add new fields, populate them, deprecate old fields</li>
    <li><strong>Schema version bump</strong>: Update <code>entdb snapshot --update</code>, deploy new server first, then clients</li>
  </ol>
</DocsLayout>
